1166 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
1177 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law not to be
1188 codified in the Oklahoma Statutes reads as follows:
1199 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Procurement
2200 Protection Act of 2026".
2211 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2222 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 85.59 of Title 74, unless there
2233 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
2244 As used in this act:
Req. No. 16530 Page 1

11 1. "Company" means any sole proprietorship, organization,
22 association, corporation, partnership, joint venture, limited
33 partnership, limited liability partnership, limited liability
44 company, or other entity or business association, including all
55 wholly owned subsidiaries, majority-owned subsidiaries, parent
66 companies, or affiliates of such entities or business associations
77 that exist for the purpose of making profit;
88 2. "Control" means:
99 a. control as defined in the Investment Company Act of
1100 1940, 15 U.S.C., Section 80a-2(a), or
1111 b in the case of a company domiciled in the People’s
1122 Republic of China, involvement in a company’s
1133 governance structure, monitoring, or internal human
1144 resources decisions of a company consistent with the
1155 objectives set out in the Opinion on Strengthening the
1166 United Front Work of the Private Economy in the New
1177 Era issued by the General Office of the Central
1188 Committee of the Chinese Communist Party (2020) or a
1199 successor or similar document;
2200 3. "Domicile" means the country in which a company is
2211 registered, the company’s affairs are primarily completed, and where
2222 the majority of ownership share is held;
2233 4. "Federally banned corporation" means any company producing
2244 designated equipment federally banned currently or banned after the
Req. No. 16530 Page 2

11 effe ctive date of this act. Such bans shall include those resulting
22 from, but not limited to, the following federal agencies and acts:
33 a. the Federal Communications Commission, including, but
44 not limited to, any equipment or service deemed to
55 pose a threat to national security identified on the
66 Covered List developed pursuant to 47 C.F.R., Section
77 1.50002 and published by the Public Safety and
88 Homeland Security Bureau of the Federal Communications
99 Commission pursuant to the federal Secure and Trusted
1100 Communications Networks Act of 2019, 47 U.S.C.,
1111 Section 1601 et seq.,
1122 b. the United States Department of Commerce,
1133 c. the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency,
1144 d. the Federal Acquisition Security Council, and
1155 e. Section 889 of the John S. McCain National Defense
1166 Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2019, P. L. 115-232;
1177 5. "Foreign adversary" means adversarial nations including the
1188 People's Republic of China, the Russian Federation, the Islamic
1199 Republic of Iran, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, the
2200 Republic of Cuba, the Venezuelan regime of Nicolás Maduro, and the
2211 Syrian Arab Republic; and
2222 6. "Foreign adversary company" means any company, other than a
2233 United States person or United States subsidiary as such terms are
2244 defined in 15 C.F.R., Section 772.1, that:
Req. No. 16530 Page 3

11 a. is domiciled, incorporated, issued, or listed in a
22 foreign adversary country,
33 b. is headquartered in a foreign adversary country,
44 c. has its principal place of business in a foreign
55 adversary country,
66 d. is controlled by the government of a foreign adversary
77 or any instrumentality thereof, or
88 e. is majority-owned by an entity controlled by the
99 government of a foreign adversary or any
1100 instrumentality thereof.
1111 If a parent company does not meet any of the criteria set forth
1122 in this paragraph and does not recognize more than fifty percent
1133 (50%) of the total annual global revenue of the parent company and
1144 subsidiaries from a foreign adversary, such parent company shall not
1155 be considered a foreign adversary company.
1166 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
1177 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 85.59a of Title 74, unless there
1188 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
1199 A. Except as provided under subsection D of this section, the
2200 following companies shall be ineligible to bid on or submit a
2211 proposal for a contract with a state agency for goods or services:
2222 1. A state-owned enterprise of a foreign adversary;
2233 2. A company domiciled within a foreign adversary;
2244 3. A foreign adversary company; or
Req. No. 16530 Page 4

11 4. A federally banned corporation.
22 B. A state agency shall require a company that submits a bid or
33 proposal with respect to a contract for goods or services to certify
44 that the company is not a company listed under subsection A of this
55 section.
66 C. If the Director of the Office of Management and Enterprise
77 Services determines that a company has knowingly submitted a false
88 certification under subsection B of this section:
99 1. The company shall be liable for a civil penalty in an amount
1100 that is equal to Two Hundred Fifty Thousand Dollars ($250,000.00) or
1111 twice the amount of the contract for which a bid or proposal was
1122 submitted, whichever is greater;
1133 2. The state agency or the Office of Management and Enterprise
1144 Services shall terminate the contract with the company; and
1155 3. The company shall be ineligible to, and shall not, bid on a
1166 state contract for sixty (60) months and shall provide proof of
1177 ownership change to the State Purchasing Director before being
1188 eligible again to bid on state contracts.
1199 D. Notwithstanding the provisions of subsection B of this
2200 section, a state agency may enter into a contract for goods
2211 manufactured by a company listed under subsection A of this section
2222 if:
2233 1. There is no other reasonable option for procuring the good;
2244 and
Req. No. 16530 Page 5

11 2. The contract is pre-approved by the Director of the Office
22 of Management and Enterprise Services after a determination that not
33 procuring the good would pose a greater threat to this state than
44 the threat associated with the procurement.
55 SECTION 4. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
